'''anapest'''

an·a·pest (also an·a·paest, anapæst)

#A metrical foot consisting of three syllables, two short and one long (e.g the word "velveteen").
#A fragment, phrase or line of poetry or verse using this meter; e.g. “Every Who down in Whoville liked Christmas a lot, but the Grinch, who lived just north of Whoville, did NOT!” ([[Dr Seuss]] aka [[Theodore Geisel]]).


[Latin ''anapaestus'', from Greek ''anapaistos'': ''ana-'' + ''paiein'', ''pais-'', to strike (an anapest is a reversed [[dactyl]])]

See ''pau(?)'' for possible [[Indo-European]] roots.

See [[anapestic]] (adj.)